‘⁸ Counsel more sure than strength in tented flelds; The soldier’s nerve for victory’s laurels wields.”

So the man who advises the crime is more guilty than he who perpe· trates it. “ For it is not by swiftness nor strength, nor agility of body, that great things are done, but by counsel, authority, and judgment;’' a truth confirmed by Tacitus: “greater things are done by consum- mate prudence than by brute force;” by Valerius Flaccus: ‘⁴ skill is often more efficient than force ;” and by Euripides also:

‘⁴ One prudent mind o'er myriad hands prevails 3 Where counsel is not, nothing else avails.”

Cicero has justly said, “ that prudence in „council is more desii-able than courage in the field, for to rush to the battle rashly, and to engage with the enemy, is something preposterous, and like the brute beasts. Arms are powerless abroad, if there be not prudence at home.”

The excesses of a foreign soldiery in Ireland, the devastation of her provinces, the plunder and conflagration of her houseS, and the mas- sacre of her sons, must be all laid at Giraldus’s door. It was his guilty counsel that inflamed the fury of the invaders against the kingdom of Ireland.
